item.title: Take Back the Night
item.description:
Take Back the Night

Take Back The Night is the earliest worldwide effort to combat sexual and interpersonal violence. The goal is to create safe communities where violence is not tolerated. Take Back the Night  honors survivors, their stories and shows our dedication to eradicating violence everywhere.

At 5 PM we will start our evening with snacks where we can come together and renew our collective commitment as a campus and community to end violence. You will have a chance to mingle with a few on and off campus resources, create t-shirts for the Clothesline Project which will be displayed in April, decorate luminaries to commemorate loved ones or display allyship, and there will be an opportunity to sign an "It's on US" pledge which calls all into the conversation of sexual assault prevention.

At 6 PM Maddy Griffin will share their vision and resources surrounding sexual violence prevention in the FM area. 

At 6:15 PM  have a survivor speak out and a "from fear to flames" event which encourages folks to share their story either in a written or verbal format with folks that  believe and support them. You could also sing a song, share a poem, or discuss artwork that you have created. We will conclude the night with s'mores and bonfires.

At 6:45 we will conclude the night with a guided meditation to ground ourselves and to prepared to dig into anti-violence work ahead of us!

All portions of this event are voluntary and support from the counseling center staff will be with us during the event. This is an event that is meant to uplift and support though difficult narratives may be told. In case of inclement weather, the event will be held in the Comstock Memorial Union Ballroom. 

This event is hosted by Moorhead’s Women’s Center, Rainbow Dragon Center, and Concordia College

MSUM is committed to creating an inclusive and accessible event. If you need a reasonable accommodation to attend this event, please contact Chuck Eade at Charles.Eade@mnstate.edu. You will be contacted individually to discuss your request.

From Thursday, September 25, 2025 5:00 PM to 7:00 PM CDT at Moorhead Campus Mall.

item.title: One Book, One Community: Author Visit with Lars Mytting
item.description:
One Book, One Community: Author Visit with Lars Mytting

In partnership, the Fargo Public Library, Moorhead Public Library, West Fargo Public Library, Concordia's Carl B. Ylvisaker Library, MSUM's Livingston Lord Library, NDSU Libraries, and the Historical and Cultural Society of Clay County, have selected The Bell in the Lake by Lars Mytting as the 2025 One Book, One Community read.

 

As part of the lineup of events for the One Book, One Community reading project, join us for an author presentation by Lars Mytting. Set in a remote part of Norway in 1879 against the backdrop of stave churches and rural traditions, this internationally acclaimed story explores the powerful tensions between faith, superstition, and personal duty. Borrow the ebook via the Libby app.

 

The event will be held in the Knutson Center Centrum on the campus of Concordia College. The doors will open at 6:30 PM. Admission is free; a book signing will follow the author's presentation. Books will be available for purchase. Parking on the Concordia Campus is free, with the following lots being in the closest proximity to The Centrum: R1, R2, G1, and G2.

 

In addition, the event will also be streamed on Concordia's site: https://video.ibm.com/channel/concordia-college

 

This program is made possible thanks to funding from the Minnesota Arts & Cultural Heritage Fund, Lake Agassiz Regional Library, and the Friends of the Fargo Public Library (major sponsors), among other generous sponsors.

 

Please visit 1book1communtiy.org for more information about the reading project and related events happening around the F-M community.

From Monday, September 29, 2025 7:00 PM to 8:00 PM CDT at Concordia College – Knutson Center Centrum.

item.title: One Book, One Community Presentation: Norwegian Migration to the United States
item.description:
One Book, One Community Presentation: Norwegian Migration to the United States

Join us for a special presentation by Dr. Sean Taylor, History Professor at MSUM, as he traces the past and present of Norwegian migration to the United States. In commemoration of the 200th anniversary of the first organized Norwegian migration, this talk will trace the historical roots of Norwegian immigration to the United States and Canada and explore how migration patterns and cultural connections to North America have transformed over time. 

 

Visit 1book1community.org for more information about the reading project and related events happening around the Fargo-Moorhead community.

item.title: Course Design Intensive (for Faculty)
item.description:
Course Design Intensive (for Faculty)

Course Design Intensive is a collaborative offering from the Faculty and Professional Learning Center and the Office of Online Learning. The one-day intensive will be offered several times throughout the year. Much of the time will be spent in hands-on work so faculty are encouraged to bring a syllabus, course shell, or course outline on which they will build.  
  

Course Design Intensive draws on well-established practices in backward course design emphasizing the writing and interpretation of meaningful student learning outcomes and mapping these outcomes to meaningful assessments (both formative and summative) and student engagement activities. The one-day intensive will be offered several times throughout the year. 

An EDD is awarded for participation for this event. Preference for face to face participation.

In celebration of Hispanic Heritage Month, LGTBQ History Month, and Banned Books Week, we invite you to celebrate your 1st Amendment right to read by joining our Banned Books Reading Group with fellow MSUM faculty, staff, and students. Bring your lunch and we'll discuss Cemetery Boys by Aiden Thomas on Monday, October 6 from 12-1 PM in the Library Porch (LI 100). Erienne Fawcett, Coordinator of Gender and Sexuality, will be leading this discussion.

 

Publisher’s description: "A trans boy determined to prove his gender to his traditional Latinx family summons a ghost who refuses to leave in Aiden Thomas's paranormal YA debut."

 

The Livingston Lord Library can help you get a print copy of the book by following these instructions:

  • Go to the book in Dragon OneSearch 
  • Sign in with your StarID
  • If our library’s copy is checked out, click on “Through Interlibrary Loan”
  • Select physical format
  • Read and acknowledge the copyright statement
  • Click “Send Request” at the bottom of the form

Otherwise, access the library's digital eBook or audiobook through our OverDrive collection and read it with the Libby app. If you need assistance, please contact Cori Edgerton at corinne.edgerton@mnstate.edu or Jean Kramer at kramer@mnstate.edu.

item.title: Halloween One-Shots
item.description:
Halloween One-Shots

Are you looking to try D&D for the first time? Looking to branch out? Or do you simply want to have a reason to wear a costume? Get ready for a day of adventure and excitement hosted by MSUM's D&D Adventurers Guild!

 

Tentative Event Schedule:

1 P.M. - Doors open; Sign up for a spot at a table! Games begin in rolling fashion.

1:30 P.M. - Most Games to begin

2:30 P.M. - Last call to join a game

5 P.M. - Fantasy costume contest and dice stacking competition

One-shots will begin as table maximums are met and filled on a first come basis. Breaks can be taken throughout at the GM's discretion. Official event break at 5pm just before costume contest begins.

 

Join us in the CMU Ballroom for this semester’s TTRPG (tabletop roleplaying game) one-shot event! Game Facilitators will host an approximately three and a half hour one-shot adventure. No experience is needed! One-shots are stories designed to be played and completed in a single session. Everyone is welcome to come and join - you do not need to be an organization member to attend. We encourage folks to bring their own set of dice, but we will try to provide dice to use at the table as needed.

 

Looking for an opportunity to run a one-shot?

Whether you're already a Game Facilitator (ex. DM, GM, etc.) with the organization or if you're newly looking for an opportunity to run a game please sign-up and provide a brief description of your one-shot (preferably by Monday, October 21st, 2024). More information and sign-up will be posted soon with the follow up form to provide us a brief description of your game.

 

Interested but unsure? You’re welcome to attend as a spectator - there’s no pressure to join a game if you’d rather just observe a one-shot. We will also have some board games and Magic: The Gathering commander decks available to play for those arriving late or not wishing to join a one-shot.

 

For those dressing up, please keep in mind the state laws of Minnesota and MSUM policies regarding firearms, explosives, other weapons, or dangerous chemicals that are not allowed at this event.

 

Below is specific policy information from the 2025-2026 Student Handbook for your convenience:

Illegal or unauthorized possession of firearms, explosives, other weapons, or dangerous chemicals on University premises or use of any such item, even if legally possessed, in a manner that harms, threatens or causes fear to others. Students are prohibited from possessing any replica of an actual firearm or knife with a blade longer than three inches that substantially duplicates an actual firearm or knife, or could be reasonably perceived to be an actual firearm or knife.

Firearms include any gun, rifle, pistol, or handgun designed to fire bullets, BBs, pellets or other projectiles by means of explosive gas, compressed air, or other propellant. Weapons include, but are not limited to, knives with a blade length more than three inches that does not have the specific purpose of food preparation, switchblades, razors, metal knuckles, bows and arrows, nun-chucks, foils, or any instrument used to threaten or inflict injury upon another person. Dangerous materials include lighter fluid, propane, or other dangerous chemicals.

 

Fake explosives or anything similar to an explosive, open flames of any kind, and glitter are additionally not allowed.

 

If you have any questions please reach out to the D&D Adventurers Guild.

From Saturday, October 25, 2025 1:00 PM to 5:00 PM CDT at Comstock Memorial Union Ballroom.
